{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_kendall_ver01/data/sn82014085/00393346826/1945101101/0494.xml":{"full_text":"Sundays and Holidays by\nrax waterbury osmograi, wo.\nBudding, Waurtmry, Oonn.\nSubscription Rates\n$10.40\n2.60\nPayable to Advance\nSix Months.\nOne Month\n.$5.20\n90c\nMember of Audit Bureau of Circulations.\nDemocrat will not return manuscript sent in for publication\nmom panted by postage. No attention paid anonymous\nMens.\nDial 4-2121\nDepartments\nDial 4*2121\nAll Departments\nTHURSDAY, OCTOBER 11, 1945\nA Thought for Today\nRemain tin the word that I said ante you, The servant Is net greater\nthan his lord. If they have persecuted me, they will also persecute\nyea; If they have kept my saying, they wlU keep yours also.\u2014 John\nUt2$.\nAttend! That thou are happy, owe to God;\nThat thou contlnuest such, owe to thyself,\nThat Is, to thy obedience; therein stand.\n\u2014Milton.\nAnchors A weigh!\n\nAdmiral Chester W. Nlmitz came to New York town\nthis week and faced one of the biggest demonstrations\nIn the history of that place which is saying some\nthing. The triumphal march of the Admiral presented\na vast moving spectacle in which uniformed men and\ncivilians mixed. Six hundred WAVES comprised the\nentr\u2019acte, and passed down the reception line, each shak\ning hands with the Admiral.\nThe hero of the sea war in the Pacific took it in\nhis stride. He was the central figure of a big scene which\nwill be duplicated as each successive hero comes home.\nSharing honors with the Admiral were thirteen Navy\nand Marine heroes who are getting top honors for their\ncontribution in the war so recently ended.\nTo many the demonstration was a stupendous, color\nful spectacle; impressive marching lines, gold braid,\nmedals, all that goes to make an impressive Navy par\nade, with the gay background of New York avenues\nwith high buildings forming the background. To others\nit was a demonstration of deep feeling, from the heart,\na splendid gesture that in some measure revealed every\nman\u2019s estimation of the Navy\u2019s stupendous contribution\nduring the conduct of the war.\nAdmiral Nimltz said: \u201cI am deeply moved, deeply\nhonored and grateful, for this warm welcome, which I\naccept in behalf of two million men of the Army, Navy,\nMarine Corps, Coast Guard, men of New Zealand, and\nmen of Great Britain who served under me, all of whom\nteamed together to defeat Japan.\" To which the vast\nassemblages probably answered\u2014Amen.\nIt was a great day for New York City, for the na\ntion and for the world. The fleet is in! The Admiral\nhas come home!\nColorful Autumn\nWhen the first touch of color gives beauty to\nAutumn; when the first killing frost has had the usual\neffects on vegetation, nature makes up for certain losses\nwith appreciable gains. The fresh green gives way to\nthe first touch of scarlet that tints the maple leaf, wood\nbine and sumac are vividly red. The Barberry hedges\ntore red berries. You note the yellows, but red hits\nyou in the eye as you drive through.the country.\nThis is the season that is formally known as\nAutumn, but somehow or other gets bracketed as Indian\nSummer. Since Indian Summer is no official season,\nit might be permissable to pick any mild season and\nso name it.\nWe like to think of it, however, as a season that\ncomes later, after the leaves are gone, a time nearer\nwinter, which was once late October or better still, Novem\nber. October days seem to express Autumn, 30-called;\nwhen a persistent sun pierces the early morning and\nnoonday haze; when a few straggling flowers survive\ntiie killing frosts; and when a vivid sunset etches the\nwestern sky. All this would be Autumn by the calendar.\nLet Indian Summer come in when the Autumn show is\ndotje; when we have had our first wintry days, and\nthere is nothing left blooming, Just the bitter sweet and\nother wild berries continuing the tradition of a colorful\nAutumn..\nOur Mild Aid To Liberty\nA few days ago an estimated quarter-million people in\netr 5-J\nA 4w n O Ugv V**\u2022***\u00bb*VU u um>\u00bb *v*\nBuenos Aires Joined in a demonstration for freedom and\nit the Argentine military dictatorship which, by re\nv\u201e.ons, threats and violence, maintains itself in power.\ncritical and social differences were forgotten as marchers\npledged ther continuing support of the constitution and\nshouted \u201cDeath to Peron!\u201d\nOn the same day a story from Washington said that\nI wartime economic sanctions Imposed by this country and\nBritain against Spain and Argentina were up for review,\nI and might be eased or abandoned.\nThe governments of these two dictator countries need\ncoal and oil. They didn\u2019t get much of cither during the war.\nBoth items were scarce. There was little for export, and the\nbulk of whatever surplus there was logically went to friend\nly countries.\nNow, though coal is still in short supply, oil is reason\nably abundant. There seems to be no economic reason why\nIncreased shipments could not be made to the two coun\nIn fact, a good excuse could probably be found for\nso in Argentina's case, since our oil exports are being\nnged there for flaxseed and linseed oils, which are\nneeded here.\njut there are urgent moral reasons why these curbs\nId be continued. Any relaxation would surely be inter\nby Franco and Peron, and by their countrymen who\n_ them, as indicating a softer Anglo-American atti\nIt would strengthen the dictators\u2019 hands. It would\nthe ordeal of freedom-loving people under their\nvictory which\ntheir Allies, have won over dictatorship and tyranny\nis a situation that has been festered by the general\n\u25a0s of British and American policy,\nmay be hoped that these two powers will not take\nto prolong the power of two pompous proteges\nunct Axis. The resistance by Franco\u2019s opponents\nout of Spain, though nearly crushed, has not died.\n>f the Argentine people are unmistakable. It\nhame If we and Britain should now withhold\naid of limited economic sanctions from these\nIn their fight for liberty.\nts out to sea for future trips\nher colon, the three fun\nThe last time she\nSomewhere, Somehow, We Got Off The Main Highway\nThe Firing Line\nBy D. N. T.\n\u201cHow carefully do you write the\naddress on a letter?\u201d\u2014From an edi\ntorial in The Boston Olobe.\nORIGINAL SIN\nDo you dearly and carefully desig\nnate\nThe street and number, and get\nthem straight?\nDo you spare the wrath of the mall\nofficials\nBy paying mind to the right ini\ntials?\nDo you not worry contention's bone,\nBut look it up and append the zone?\nAre you sure you've written the\nproper station?\nAnd how about the abbreviation?\nHave you got \"N. H.\" that appears\n\u201cN. J.\"\nOr \"Cal.\" for \"Col.\" or the other\nway,\nOr, prithee, do state and city drib\nble\nInto a bleak, unllghted scribble?\nWrite addresses and keep them\nclean\nBo the postal neophyte\u2014or dean\u2014\nIs never banking on second guesses\nIn trying to make the said ad\ndresses.\n(That Is the word that never falls\nTo please the men who man the\nmalls;\nI offer it now to my peers and bet\nters.\nMY trouble is that I can\u2019t write\nletters.)\n\"Prosperous Nations Should Help\nLesa Fortunate, Elsenhower Says\u201d\u2014\nheadline. And one significant thing\nwill strike most of us on .reading\nthat head: What Is the \"s\" doing\non the end of the second word?\nWho says that the Japs are not\nquick to catch on to the American\nway of life? Students at a Tokyo\nhigh school already are out on\nstrike over the Issue of removing\nthe school principal.\nThe Springfield Morning Union\nrecently referred to a football game\nbetween \"Dortmouth\" and Pennsyl\nvania. Of course, anyone north of\nBoston knows that it should have\nbeen \"Dahtmouth.\"\nOur Navy has drawn plans far a\npostwar fleet In which aircraft car\nriers will be given secondary posi\ntion. It probably expects to wait\nfor a tidal wavs to carry the ship\nthat carries the atomic bomb into\nenemy territory.\nA Labor member of Parliament\nsays that this country wants Eng\nland to become an \"American col\nony.\" If that Is part of our post\nwar plan, we at least have a his\ntorical example of how not to run it.\nAdmiral Nimitz says that Japan\nwas brought to the point of sur\nrender by seapower which made\npossible the use of the atomic\nbomb. Partisans of the plane still\nwonder what would have happened\nif everything hadn't gone Just right\nand we weren\u2019t up in the air about\nit. I\nWaterbary\nof The Past\n25 Yeani Ago\nA man wu being accidentally\nelectrocuted at ScovilTs while re\npairing wires.\nDog owners were being warned to\nkeep their pets at home unless li\ncensed.\n15 Yearn Ago\nThe first edition of Crosby High\nSchool\u2019s newspaper, Argus, was be\ning read by proud students.\nBillie Dove was playing in \"One\nNight at Busies\" at the Strand.\n6 Years Ago\nThe usual procedure wu being\nreversed when a mis, rather than\na woman, was suing for breach of\npromise in a local court.\nViews Of The Press\nCONFUSING THE VETERAN\n(Hartford Oourant)\nCommander John F. Robinson,\nstate director of Selective Service,\nsems somewhat surprised that his\nrecent announcement designating\nlocal draft boards as \"official fed\neral veterans' Information centers\"\nshould cause misunderstanding or\nconfusion. It Is a fact, as pointed\nout by him, that demobilised sol\ndiers must report to their local\ndraft board within ten days of their\nreturn home. Some report In per\nson, others by telephone or letter.\nIt Is also the responsibility of Se\nlective Service to see that a vet\neran gets the protection of the O. I.\nBill of Rights In enforcing his olalm\nto his former Job.\nBeyond that, however, Selective\nService boards are nothing more\nthan a referral agency. It would\nbe unfortunate If veterans gained\nthe impression that Selective\nService had the facilities and the\npersonnel to perform the work that\nIs being done by so many locally\norganised veterans' centers, a fact\nthat Is implied in Commander\nRobinson's original anonuncement\nthat he was prepared to \"advise\nand assist with his other problems.\"\nThis merely set* up an intervening\nagency between the veteran and the\nworking agency that will do the\nactual job, a practice that has been\ndescribed as the \"veterans\u2019 run\naround,\" to avoid which local vet\nerans' centers were organised.\nHowever, the basic conflict lies\nIn the overt and covert opposition\nto veterans' centers on a local basis\nas expressed by agents of Selective\nService. In Norwich, Connecticut,\nthis week funds for a local vet\nerans\u2019 center were withheld follow\ning the statement of a draft board\nclerk that he was doing the work\nand would continue to do the work\nso that the expenditure of funds\nwas unnecessary. In Middletown a\nsimilar resolution was tabled for\nthe same reason.\nThere Is a place for Selective\nService boards In the large frame\nwork of re-employment and read\njustment of veterans. But the heart\nof this lies in the local veterans'\ncenters and not, as Commander\nRobinson has said, In his own or\nganization.\nA part of the difficulty stems\nfrom the fact that the State of\nConnecticut was far ahead of Se\nlective Service In anticipating what\nwould be needed,. In many states\nthat organization must perforce\ncarry the whole load because local\ncommunities have not been organ\nized to do their share of the work.\nBut quite a different picture per\nvalls in most Connecticut commu\nnities where active, working centers\nhave been in operation for a year\nor more. The situation could easily\nbe clarified by a clear-cut state\nment by Commander Robinson to\nhis subordinates that they should\nfoster rather than hinder the cre\nation of additional veterans' cen\nters by the local communities. It\nIs this local self-help that Is the\nbedrock on which Governor Bald\nwin\u2019s re-employment program has\nbeen based. It Is a philosophy that\nshould be emphasized rather than\nsmothered under the refrain that\n\"Washington will do It.\u201d\nMORE rOWER TO HIM\n(Hartford Times)\nMore power to Andrew Flore, a\nveteran of this war who lives In\nWatcrbury.\nHe won his second lieutenancy by\na promotion In the field after he\nrisked his life to save nine men\nfrom a burning jilane In New\nGuinea. He also was awarded the\nSoldier's Medal.\nLieutenant Flore we should\ngive him the distinction of his\nhard-won military title\u2014runs a\ngasoline filling station, which the\ngasoline drouth due to the strike\nthreatened to close. Perhaps he\nIs over that hump now. In any\nevent, he could not afford to have\nthat happen. He Is getting only\nISO a week although he works nearly\n18 hours a day. He needs that\nIncome.\nAnd he didn\u2019t propose to lose It\nbecause of a strike.\nHe was willing to go to New\nHaven and obtain gas and force his\nway through picket lines, If neces\nsary. If trouble started it was those\nwho caused it, not he, who would\nhave to take the consequences.\nLieutenant Flore knows what\ndanger Is. He knows what death\nIs. He has faced It. He has been\nengaged In work Important enough\nso that he doesn't propose to be\npushed around while legitimately\ncarrying on a legitimate business\non which his livelihood depends.\nBully for him.\nIf there were more of that spirit,\non the part of the general public, on\nthe part of public officials, on the\npart of those who make the laws,\nthe reign of terrorism and economic\ndesolation which threatens, and to\na degree Is here, would be snuffed\nout In the short order which It\ndeserves.\nWe can only wish that auch a\nsplendid example might produce\nuseful results. 1\nNOT ALL CANDY\nLicorice Is thought of as a con\nfection, but more than one-half of\nthe licorice used in the United\nStates Is utilized in the tobacco In\ndustry, with the balance Used for\ncandy and drugs.\n(CARNIVAL\nBy DICK TURNER\npeerless\nLAONDRy\nMerry-Go-Round By Drew Pearson\nWASHINGTON, Oct 11\u2014The Secret Sendee has\na harder time keeping pace with Harry\nthan any other President In yeara\u2014especially\nhe's back in his home stamping grounds. Truman\nlorn to mingle with friends, darts\nhere and there in crowds, can\u2019t\nmem to get used to the fact that\nhe\u2019s President. Par It years,\n8.8. men got into the habit of\nstanding around Roosevelt He\nmoved slowly and Infrequently.\nThey did the same. Now they have\nto Jump. Old friends at\nTruman's sometimes resent Se\ncret Service men getting in front\nof him when they approach. Two\nchildren who knew .him started to\ngreet the President in front of\nthe Truman home some time ago, but the 8.8. men\nbrusquely planted themselves in their path.\nPeople In Independence, Mo., appreciate the way\nMrs. Truman, daughter Margaret, and the Presi\ndent himself have been homefolks with them, but\nthey don\u2019t like the Secret Service.\nAll summer, newsmen have been trying to get\nphotographs of the inside of the summer White\nHouse\u2014without suocess. They have begged and im\nplored Mrs. Truman to let them have some Informal\nshots of henelf Inside the old family home. But Mrs.\nT. has been adamant. On one occasion, the\nPresident obligingly agreed to pose on the lawn with\nmembers of his family. He and Margaret arrived and\nwaited for Mrs. Truman. She didn\u2019t come. Finally\nthe President went inside the house to get her. In\na few minutes he came out without his wife.\n\"Well go ahead with the pictures now,\u201d he said\nquietly. There was no further comment. Obvi\nously Mrs. Truman had refuMd to budge.\nFriends say that one reason for Mrs. Truman\u2019s\npress-shyness is an attempt to be the opposite of\nMrs. Roosevelt. This not because Mrs. T is critical\nof Mrs, Roosevelt, but rather becaum she never was\nin the public eye, has spent all her life as a housewife\nand believes in continuing to do the same. Mrs.\nTruman feels that personal appearances are not down\nher alley and that she should stick to what she\ndoes naturally. Another factor may be that\nthe summer White House belongs to Mrs. Truman's\nmother, Mrs. D. W. Wallace, and Mrs. Wallace is\nquite a dominant force in the Truman family.\nMrs. Wallace believes that a home is a home. It Is\nnot a place to be photographed on the inside, it is\na place to live in.\nMrs. Wallace, now in her eighties, has decided\nideas on a lot of things, at one time Including her\nson-in-law. Everybody in Independence knows that\nHarry Truman courted Bess Wallace for a long time\nand tliat the Wallace family didn\u2019t approve of him.\nThey thought he would never amount to much. The\nWallaces were elders in the Presbyterian church, and\nHarry was a Baptist. They were among the most solid\ncltlMns of Independence, and Harry had a very hap\nhasard business career. So it was.not until Harry\ncame back from World War I at the age of 35\nthat the Wallace family consented to have their\ndaughter, then about 83, marry the man who later\nbecame President.\n\nHarry Truman\u2019s hospitality nearly precipitated\na newspaper civil war when he visited Independence\nlast month. Mayor Roger T. Sermon gave his usual\nstag poker party of old friends for the President, and\nTruman Invited two newspapermen, Merrlman Smith\nof the United Press and Ernest Vaocaro of the Asso\nciated Press. They, together with Bob Nixon of the\nInternational News Service (but who did not take\nthe Independence trip) have travelled with\nfor about 30,000 .miles, ao ha invited them to\nto the party as off-the-record guests. Other\nnewsmen were not invited. When Smith and Vaocaro\nreturned, their oolleagues asked where they had\nbeen. \"Out with some girls,\u201d they replied. trying to\nprotect Truman. Later, when the uninvited\nnewsmen dlamvered where the AP and UP corres\npondents actually were, they nearly disrupted a party\ngiven by Editor Roy Roberts of the Kansas City I\nHugh DeUcy, scrappy freshman\nfrom Seattle, asked the $M guestom at a _\nsession of the Naval Affairs Committee. Admiral\nDenfeld,\u201d he asked the new chief of naval personnel,\n\"In view of the fact that It was the Navy and the\nMarine Corps who really did the major port of the\nfighting In the Pacific, don\u2019t you think It would have\nbeen proper to make a naval officer supreme com\nmander In Japan?\u201d Admr. Denfeld grinned but did\nnot answer. Although their children may like It,\nthe parents of the Alexandria, Va., Sunday school\nclass taught by Oen. Harry Vaughan, President Tru\nman\u2019s Military Aide, are worried about the President\u2019s\nweek-end trips. Vaughan always accompanies his\nboss, so the children miss a great many Sunday\nschool lessons. Members of the Officers\u2019dub\nat Port Meyre, Va., were upset because, when Pres\nldent Truman visited there recently, he didn\u2019t stop to\nthe club-house. They had had all the slot machines\nremoved to preparation for his visit Comdr.\nGene Tunney, farmer heavyweight champion, is plan\nnlng to make a atab at the Connecticut Senate seat\nnow held by Admr. Tommy Hart, who was appointed\nto succeed the late Francis Maloney. Eric John\nston, who has taken over the movie Job formerly\nheld by Will Hays, Is planning the construction of a\nhuge Motion Picture Industry building here to Wash\nington. It would house offices of the picture com\npanies, as well as work space for camera crews\nfftywiHng to Washington and facilities for theatermen,\nacton, studio workers and anyone else connected with\nthe Industry.\n\nThe greatest living expert on atomic energy,\nWemer Heisenberg, has disappeared. His where\nabouts remain a complete mystery. The War Depart\nment won\u2019t say whether he was captured by the\nAllies or escaped them. Heisenberg Is recognised as\nthe world\u2019s leading nuclear P^clst He\nb\u00abH<ng in Spain or Argentina. Both of these countries\nhave sufficient resources to develop atomic bombs\nA secret Nasi file linking every Important Oer\nman Industrialist with the Nasi party even before\nHitler came Into power to 1933 has Just been discov\nert by the American Army. Watch for development!\non this when the war trials open.. On Nov. V\nthe Army will stop microfilming V-mril after doing\nthe stupendous Job of carrying 1,750,000,000 V-msll\nletters. Families with V-mall forms on their hands,\nhowever, can still use them. The Army wiU ttort\nthey\u2019re delivered as regular mall wlthoutmlcrofUrn\ntog Secretary Fred Vinson Is by all odds the\n.istesman-u\u00a3 negotiator to the BritUh con\nferencee for poet-war help. Oen.\nthe U. S. Army Is preparing appeals to Congress to\nappropriate several hundred million dolUrt to feed\nGermans this winter. However, Oen. Hlldrtog has\nasked for no appropriations to feed toe starring\nDutch, Czechs, Poles, Belgians, French and Nor\nwegians who face the most difficult winter ln hls\ntory because these same Germans destroyed tneu\ncountries. Henry Morgentoau\u2019s new book pub\nlished this week reveals for the first time startling\nnew facts regarding our treatment of\nis called \u201cQermany is our Problem,\" and after read\ning the book you are convinced that It la._\nRetire At Birth\nBy Peter Edson\nWASHINGTON, Oct. 11\u2014With all this talk fly*\nIns around about |2S for 36 weeks of no work, 53\nhours\u2019 pay for 40 hours' work, tax cuts, rollbacks,\ncarryovers, refunds and heaven knows what other\nnew economic theories, you still\nhaven\u2019t heard anything unless you\nknow about the \"Morrow Plan.\"\nIts slogan Is, \u201cRetire at Birth.\u201d\nIts sub-slogan Is, \u2018\u2018Work for\nLuxury.\u201d\nThe Morrow Plan was first\ncooked up as a gag, back at the\nend of the 1030\u2019s when the \"Ham\nand Eggs\u201d and \u2019Thirty Dollars\nEvery Thursday\" movements were\nsweeping the country. In those\ndays when Father Coughlin, Doc\n\u25a0won Townsend, Gerald L. K, Smith\nor any other theorist with a cure for the depression\ncould get an audience, a couple of Columbus, Ohio,\n-woke up to the fact that unless some\nwas done pretty quickly, the Ham and\na good chance of carrying the state In\nthe 1040 elections.\n\nSince nobody wanted to listen to reason, these\nnewspapermen decided the best way to lick the\ncrack-brained theories was to reduce them to ab\nsurdity and laugh them to death. So they dreamed up\nthe plan to end all plans. They called it the Morrow\nPlan because the man who thought It up was named\nWalt Morrow. Since those carefree days, this Morrow\nhis become a conservative business representative In\nWashington and he says today that the Morrow plan\nof half a dosen years ago couldn\u2019t begin to compete\nwith some of the economic theories being concocted\ntoday to cure postwar depression Ills.\nFirst step in the dlssy conception of the original\nMorrow plan Wi to Incorporate tne unneci\nof America and run It ae one big business, withal!\nthe cltiaens being entitled to share in the profits.\nEvery cittern at birth, automatically would become s\nbond-holder and would be issued, free, *80,000 worth\nof non-transferable bonds which would be canceled\nat death. During life, however, the Income from these\nbonds, at a conservative 8 per cent Interest, would\nyield $2,800 income a year.\n\u2022Oils Interest money would be paid in a kind of\nscrip which would be good to purchase the neceTi\ntles of life\u2014food, rent, clothing and <\u00a3)CtSLbUJt\u201c5\u00a3\nnothing more. If you were content\u00bb,\n$2,800, without luxuries, you could do it Hence the\nslogan, \u201cRetire at Birth.\"\nAmbitious people, the folks who wanted the lux\nuries of life, still would be permitted to work for\nthem in the old-fashioned way if they chose to go to\nthat trouble.\nAfter Morrow thought up this dtay acbwne\ndecided to try it out. His associate was Parker La\nMoore, who is now about to be discharged from the\nArmy as a lieu tenant-colonel.\nMorrow would find a crowd and go Into his act.\nWhen he finished explaining his plan he would ask,\n\u201cHow does it sound to you?\"\nAnd then, to the absolute amassment of both\nMorrow and LaMoore, instead of saying* You re\naway!\" their listeners would invariably say, \u201cIt sounds\nall rlghtl\"\nThat cured Morrow and LaMoore of trying to\nout-screwball the screwballs. The Morrow plan was\nallowed to die. It is revived here now only to help\nexplain why some of the slogans now being carried\nonplacards in parades and picket lines have so many\nwilling followers. _\nOdds And Ends -fry Bil1 Cunningham\nIt'S to be hoped to the Almighty that we have\nplenty of oil stored In the Pacific. If these strikes\nreally stall our fleets, fanatic rebellion suddenly\nsweeps Japan, and there's no way to get any help to\nour men, Bataan would fade Intq\nInsignificance. Remember the Jap\nanese army, supposed to have\n000,000 men, was fully trained,\nfully armed, fully needled to fight\nIt out with the Americans, and\nthen didn't have the chance\nPew men have earned money a\nharder way, but It\u2019s nice to know\nthat Oen. Jonathan Wainwrlght\nsurvived his tribulations to find\na pot of gold. Back pay to the\nsum of some $00,000 awaited him.\nCunningham Newspaper syndicates ran the\nbidding for his personal story up to $188,000, and\nIf he wants to go In for public appearances, a movie\ntreatment of his story, maybe the radio and similar\nthings, his bitter experience will gross him several\nhundred thousand dollars.\nAlter listening to an tne snavmg oeing none in\nthe World Series broadcasts, reminds this brush and\nlather man that Oasey fltengal, formerly a major\nleague ball yard bird of brilliant plumage himself,\nIs the only man I ever saw who could shavs without\na mirror. Ol\u2019 Case always squared off to one, and\nhe may have used It when alone, but If he had com\npany, he'd get to talking, turn half way away from\nit toward his vls-a-vls, face neither the one nor the\nother and keep right on hoeing. He alwayk did a\ngood Job and he was fast with It, too. Some of the\nscribes were hammering poor Oase near the end of\nhis managerial ministrations, but the game, at least,\nwas a lot funnier when he was around.\n\nIncome taxes are to be cut five Mlllon dollars,\nbut those who pay real Income taxes will only read\nabout It. I told you about that covey of new\nAMO's and UNRA\u2019s I saw flying In to earry on for\nus in Europe. Dispatches from good reporters report\nthe pressure already Is on from them to treat the\npoor Oermans better. Prom my own experienc, I\nagree with one of the scribes who maintains that\nanybody coming over to work with the Oermans\nshould first see Britain, Prance, Holland, Belgium\nand some more. Oermany will shock the newcomer\nas a badly pulverised nation, but If he sees the other*\nfirst, he\u2019ll have the true perspective, and have the\ntruer conception of what his real duty Is.,\nHold the book open on the Patton story. There\u2019s\na lot more to It than meets the eye. Whatever\nbecame of Winston Churchill? I know a J\nwho was talking with a certain sup\n.*o do\ncaptured from the Oermana. The Japaneee war wm\natm on at the Ume, and the Senator aald It struck\nhim aa a perfect aolutlon to give the weapona to the\nOhlneae who were badly In need of irmi. The Oevman\n88 cannon, unlveraaUy conceded to be one of the\ngreateet weapona produced In the war, waa the grade\n\u201cf ordinance being eapedally dlacuaaed.The genera)\naald he had thought of auch a aolutlon but had\nthought beat to discard It leat a demand be created\nfor that type of ammunition. The Senator then\nthat danger wouldn\u2019t automatically be elim\ninated by the complete diamantllng of the German\narmament worka. The general replied that he\u2019d heard\nof no auch program.\n\nBy the way, what to our program? The war\u2019* been\nover five monthe. What are we going to do with\nGermany? When do we atart? One of the\ngreateet anomaUea In the world of aport to that\nbaaebell, auppoaedly a atandardtoed game, to tha\nleaat atandardtoed of any. A man playing In